Giuseppe Vasi was a member of the Academia di San Luca. He was one of the most important engravers of the views of Rome and considered as one of the most important engravers of the eighteenth century. Vasi's Itinerario enjoyed considerable success during XVIII century quickly becoming the most popular guidebooks among the Grand Tour travelers as well as the Christian pilgrims. This is a pocket sized volume with small scale rametti engravings and lengthy descriptions of the monuments of Rome both ancient and modern. It is composed according to an eight-day route structured through stazioni or giornate (days) each one offering a different tour through the city. This work was part of Vasi's bigger editorial project Magnificenze comprising ten volumes and dedicated to the most spectacular monuments in the city of Rome. This first edition of the Itinerario is often considered as the agile and concise guide to be used as companion to the Magnificenze.

body.value: Church of San Lorenzo in Lucina. Piazza di San Lorenzo in Lucina is the square in front of San Lorenzo in Lucina, the church to which it owes its name.
Church of Santa Maria in Ara Coeli (named as S. Maria in Araceli)
Church of Santi Luca e Martina (named as S. Martina). The entry mentions the Compagnia dei Pittori in 1588, but not the change of the name of the church to Santi Luca e Martina.
Church of Trinità dei Monti (named as Trinità sul monte Pincio)

Altemps Palace at Monte Cavallo. This guidebook reports Altemps Palace as belonging to its most recent owners, the Pallavicini-Rospigliosi family (about 1704–present). It does not mention the chain of previous owners: Scipione Borghese Caffarelli (1577–1633), about 1605–1616; Duke Giovanni Angelo Altemps (1587–1620), about 1616–1619; Guido Bentivoglio (1579–1644); Cardinal Giulio Mazarino (1602–1661), until about 1704; and the Pallavicini-Rospigliosi family (about 1704–present).
Church of San Lorenzo ai Monti (named as S. Lorenzolo)

Church of Santa Maria Rotonda (Pantheon). The Pantheon became known as Sancta Maria ad Martyres in 609 CE, when Pope Boniface IV converted the pagan temple into a Christian basilica and moved the remains of many martyrs from the Christian catacombs to this site.
Church of San Luigi dei Francesci (named as S. Luigi de’ Francesi)
Church of San Nicola dei Lorenesi (named as S. Niccolò)
Church of Sant'Angelo in Pescheria (named as Chiesa di S. Michele Arcangelo in Pescheria)
Savelli Palace (named as Teatro di Marcello, e Palazzo Orsini)
Church of San Giovanni dei Fiorentini (named as S. Giovanni Batista de’ Fiorentini)
Oratory of Sant'Orsola della Pietà (named as Oratorio della Pietà, e Consolato de’ Fiorentini)
Hospital of Santo Spirito (named as Spedale di Santo Spirito in Sassia)

Genzano. This entry describes the history of the small town of Genzano in the outskirts of Rome since antiquity, when it was known as Cintiano, to the time the castle and estate became the property of the aristocratic Cesarini family.
